        <section id="basics">
            <h2>1. The Core Language of Forex</h2>
            <p>Forex trading is the simultaneous buying of one global currency and selling of another. They are always priced in <strong>Pairs</strong>.</p>
            
            <div class="box box-blue">
                <h3>Base vs. Quote Currency Hierarchy</h3>
                <p>In the pair <strong>EUR/USD = 1.08500</strong>:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Base Currency (EUR):</strong> The first currency listed. It always represents exactly <strong>1 unit</strong>.</li>
                    <li><strong>Quote Currency (USD):</strong> The second currency listed. It indicates how much of that currency is needed to purchase 1 single unit of the base currency.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <h3>Pips vs. Pipettes Calculation</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Pip (Percentage in Point):</strong> The 4th decimal place in most pairs (0.00<u>1</u>0). It measures standard price change value. For Japanese Yen (JPY) pairs, it is the 2nd decimal place (150.<u>2</u>0).</li>
                <li><strong>Pipette:</strong> The 5th decimal place (0.0010<u>5</u>). It represents a fractional pip (1/10th of a pip).</li>
            </ul>

            <div class="box box-info">
                <strong>🧮 Simple Mathematical Formula:</strong><br>
                <code>Trade Profit/Loss = (Exit Price - Entry Price) &times; Position Lot Size</code><br><br>
                <em>Example:</em> If EUR/USD advances from 1.05200 to 1.05250, that equals a 5-pip (50-pipette) gain.
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="ecosystem">
            <h2>2. The Forex Ecosystem Players</h2>
            <p>Understanding the exact relationships within the marketplace prevents beginner exploitation:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>The Market:</strong> A decentralized network consisting of central banks, commercial banks, and multi-billion dollar hedge funds shifting capital globally.</li>
                <li><strong>The Trader (You):</strong> A retail market speculator analyzing patterns to capture price movements.</li>
                <li><strong>The Broker:</strong> A commercial entity that connects your computer to the banking network infrastructure via a trading platform.</li>
            </ul>
            
            <div class="box box-warning">
                <h3>⚠️ Crucial Safety Checklist for Choosing a Broker</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li><strong>Strict Regulation:</strong> Verify credentials ONLY with premium regulatory bodies: FCA (UK), ASIC (Australia), NFA (USA), or CySEC (Europe).</li>
                    <li><strong>The Account Manager Red Flag:</strong> Legitimate regulatory rules strictly forbid brokers from trading for you. If someone claims they can manage your account for guaranteed profits, it is a scam.</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="leverage">
            <h2>3. Leverage Configurations (1:500 vs. 1:3000 vs. Unlimited)</h2>
            <p>Leverage is temporary capital loaned by your broker, allowing you to secure massive contracts using a nominal cash margin deposit.</p>
            
            <div class="grid-2">
                <div class="box box-info">
                    <h3>✔️ The Tactical Advantages</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Allows small accounts to take meaningful setups without locking up cash requirements.</li>
                        <li>High capital efficiency; allows deployment of multiple diversified strategies simultaneously.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
                <div class="box box-warning">
                    <h3>❌ The Real Downside Risks</h3>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Instant Liquidation:</strong> With an ultra-high 1:3000 setup, a tiny 2-pip flash spike against you can completely wipe out your entire balance.</li>
                        <li><strong>Variable Tiers:</strong> Brokers offering "Unlimited" options automatically lower leverage constraints right before high-impact economic news releases to protect themselves, causing sudden margin calls.</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="spreads">
            <h2>4. Calculating & Minimizing Spreads</h2>
            <p>The spread acts as your direct broker transaction fee. It represents the instantaneous difference between market pricing options:</p>
            <p class="box box-blue"><strong>Spread Formula: Spread = Ask Price (Buy Price) - Bid Price (Sell Price)</strong></p>
            
            <h3>Strategic Execution Windows</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>When to execute trades:</strong> Trade solely when market liquidity peaks. This happens during major session overlaps (London & New York). Spreads are tightly compressed during these hours.</li>
                <li><strong>When to avoid execution:</strong> Avoid trading precisely at 5:00 PM EST (New York daily rollover). Liquidity drops completely out of the interbank network for 30 minutes, causing spreads to widen drastically.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="risk">
